    }
  ],
  "forensic": {
    "category": "network",
    "riskLevel": "medium",
    "suspiciousPatterns": []
  },
  "aiHints": {
    "analysisContext": "Snoop (RFC 1761) global header: magic(8B='snoop\\0\\0\\0') + version(4B BE, =2) + datalinkType(4B BE). Packet record structure: originalLength(4B BE) + includedLength(4B BE) + recordLength(4B BE, padded to 4B boundary) + cumulativeDrops(4B BE) + timestampSeconds(4B BE) + timestampMicroseconds(4B BE) + packetData(includedLength bytes, padded). Datalink 0=Ethernet. Wireshark reads snoop natively (wiretap library). Snoop was a Solaris-only tool; modern captures use PCAP or PCAPNG. The .cap extension is shared with PCAP — use magic to distinguish.",
    "suggestedInspections": [
      "Bytes 0-7: 'snoop\\0\\0\\0' — confirm Snoop magic vs PCAP (0xD4C3B2A1) or PCAPNG (0x0A0D0D0A)",
      "Bytes 8-11 (uint32 BE): version — should be 2 (RFC 1761)",
      "Bytes 12-15 (uint32 BE): datalink type — 0=Ethernet is most common",
      "Offset 16+: packet records — each has 6×uint32 header + packet data padded to 4B"
    ]
  },
  "software": [
    "Solaris snoop(1M) (native creator)",
    "Wireshark (read/write conversion)",
    "tcpdump (reads snoop files)",
    "NetworkMiner (forensics)"
  ],
  "formatRelationships": {
    "category": "Network",
    "extensions": [".snoop", ".cap"],
    "relatedFormats": ["PCAP", "PCAPNG", "ETHERPEEK", "NETTL"],
    "note": "Snoop is the Solaris equivalent of libpcap PCAP. Both .snoop and .cap extensions are used; .cap is shared with PCAP. Snoop is big-endian (SPARC origin) while PCAP is self-describing endianness. PCAPNG is the modern successor to both."
  },
  "MimeTypes": [
    "application/octet-stream"
  ],
  "UseCases": [
    "Legacy Solaris network troubleshooting and packet capture analysis",
    "Converting old snoop archives to PCAPNG for modern tools",
    "Network forensics on Solaris/SunOS systems",
    "Protocol debugging in legacy SPARC/Solaris environments"
  ],
